ber">Composite numbers</a> can be arranged into <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Rectangle" title=3D"Rectangle">rectangles</a> but prime numbe=
rs cannot.</figcaption></figure>
<p>A <b>prime number</b> (or a <b>prime</b>) is a <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Natural_number" title=3D"Natural number">natural number</a>=
 greater than 1 that is not a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prod=
uct_(mathematics)" title=3D"Product (mathematics)">product</a> of two small=
er natural numbers. A natural number greater than 1 that is not prime is ca=
lled a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Composite_number" title=3D"=
Composite number">composite number</a>. For example, 5 is prime because the=
 only ways of writing it as a product, <span class=3D"nowrap">1 =C3=97 5</s=
pan> or <span class=3D"nowrap">5 =C3=97 1</span>, involve 5 itself. However=
, 4 is composite because it is a product (2&nbsp;=C3=97&nbsp;2) in which bo=
th numbers are smaller than 4. Primes are central in <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Number_theory" title=3D"Number theory">number theory</a>=
 because of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fundamental_theore=
m_of_arithmetic" title=3D"Fundamental theorem of arithmetic">fundamental th=
eorem of arithmetic</a>: every natural number greater than 1 is either a pr=
ime itself or can be <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Factorization=
" title=3D"Factorization">factorized</a> as a product of primes that is uni=
que <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Up_to" title=3D"Up to">up to</=
a> their order.
</p><p>The property of being prime is called <b>primality</b>. A simple but=
 slow <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Primality_test" title=3D"Pri=
mality test">method of checking the primality</a> of a given number <span c=
lass=3D"nowrap">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-i=
nline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D=
"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=
=3D"{\displaystyle n}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
