t">AKS primality test</a>, which always produces the correct answer in <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polynomial_time" class=3D"mw-redirect"=
 title=3D"Polynomial time">polynomial time</a> but is too slow to be practi=
cal. Particularly fast methods are available for numbers of special forms, =
such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mersenne_number" class=3D"=
mw-redirect" title=3D"Mersenne number">Mersenne numbers</a>. As of October&=
nbsp;2024<sup class=3D"plainlinks noexcerpt noprint asof-tag update" style=
=3D"display:none;"><a class=3D"external text" href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/w/index.php?title=3DPrime_number&amp;action=3Dedit">[update]</a></sup> =
the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Largest_known_prime_number" ti=
tle=3D"Largest known prime number">largest known prime number</a> is a Mers=
enne prime with 41,024,320 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Numeric=
al_digit" title=3D"Numerical digit">decimal digits</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
GIMPS-2024_1-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Prime_number#cite_note-GIMPS-2024-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-2" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_number#cite=
_note-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>There are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Infinite_set" tit=
le=3D"Infinite set">infinitely many</a> primes, as <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Euclid%27s_theorem" title=3D"Euclid's theorem">demonstrate=
d by Euclid</a> around 300&nbsp;BC. No known simple formula separates prime=
 numbers from composite numbers. However, the distribution of primes within=
 the natural numbers in the large can be statistically modelled. The first =
result in that direction is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pr=
ime_number_theorem" title=3D"Prime number theorem">prime number theorem</a>=
, proven at the end of the 19th century, which says roughly that the <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability" title=3D"Probability">proba=
bility</a> of a randomly chosen large number being prime is inversely <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Proportionality_(mathematics)" title=3D=
"Proportionality (mathematics)">proportional</a> to its number of digits, t=
hat is, to its <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm" title=3D=
"Logarithm">logarithm</a>.
</p><p>Several historical questions regarding prime numbers are still unsol=
ved. These include <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goldbach%27s_co=
njecture" title=3D"Goldbach's conjecture">Goldbach's conjecture</a>, that e=
very even integer greater than 2 can be expressed as the sum of two primes,=
 and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Twin_prime" title=3D"Twin=
 prime">twin prime</a> conjecture, that there are infinitely many pairs of =
primes that differ by two. Such questions spurred the development of variou=
s branches of number theory, focusing on <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Analytic_number_theory" title=3D"Analytic number theory">analytic</a=
> or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algebraic_number_theory" titl=
e=3D"Algebraic number theory">algebraic</a> aspects of numbers. Primes are =
used in several routines in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inform=
ation_technology" title=3D"Information technology">information technology</=
a>, such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Public-key_cryptograph=
y" title=3D"Public-key cryptography">public-key cryptography</a>, which rel=
ies on the difficulty of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integer_f=
actorization" title=3D"Integer factorization">factoring</a> large numbers i=
nto their prime factors. In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abstra=
ct_algebra" title=3D"Abstract algebra">abstract algebra</a>, objects that b=
ehave in a generalized way like prime numbers include <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_element" title=3D"Prime element">prime elements</=
a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_ideal" title=3D"Prime=
 ideal">prime ideals</a>.
</p>
