<p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rhind_Mathematical_Papyrus"=
 title=3D"Rhind Mathematical Papyrus">Rhind Mathematical Papyrus</a>, from =
around 1550 BC, has <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Egyptian_fract=
ion" title=3D"Egyptian fraction">Egyptian fraction</a> expansions of differ=
ent forms for prime and composite numbers.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-14" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_number#cite_note-=
14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup> However, the earliest surviving records of the study of pri=
me numbers come from the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Greek_mat=
hematics" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Greek mathematics">ancient Greek m=
athematicians</a>, who called them <span title=3D"Ancient Greek (to 1453)-l=
anguage romanization"><i lang=3D"grc-Latn">pr=C5=8Dtos arithm=C3=B2s</i></s=
pan> (<span title=3D"Ancient Greek (to 1453)-language text"><span lang=3D"g=
rc">=CF=80=CF=81=E1=BF=B6=CF=84=CE=BF=CF=82 =E1=BC=80=CF=81=CE=B9=CE=B8=CE=
=BC=E1=BD=B8=CF=82</span></span>). <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Euclid" title=3D"Euclid">Euclid</a>'s <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Euclid%27s_Elements" title=3D"Euclid's Elements">Elements</a></i> (=
c. 300 BC) proves the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Infinitude_o=
f_primes" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Infinitude of primes">infinitude o=
f primes</a> and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fundamental_t=
heorem_of_arithmetic" title=3D"Fundamental theorem of arithmetic">fundament=
al theorem of arithmetic</a>, and shows how to construct a <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Perfect_number" title=3D"Perfect number">perfect n=
umber</a> from a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mersenne_prime" t=
itle=3D"Mersenne prime">Mersenne prime</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-stillwell-20=
10-p40_15-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P=
