essions</a> contain infinitely many primes.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-26" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_number#cite_note=
-26"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>26<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup>
</p><p>Many mathematicians have worked on <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Primality_test" title=3D"Primality test">primality tests</a> for nu=
mbers larger than those where trial division is practicably applicable. Met=
hods that are restricted to specific number forms include <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P%C3%A9pin%27s_test" title=3D"P=C3=A9pin's test">P=
=C3=A9pin's test</a> for Fermat numbers (1877),<sup id=3D"cite_ref-27" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_number#cite_=
note-27"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>27<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Proth%27s_the=
orem" title=3D"Proth's theorem">Proth's theorem</a> (c. 1878),<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-28" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pri=
me_number#cite_note-28"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>28<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Lucas%E2%80%93Lehmer_primality_test" title=3D"Lucas=E2=80=93Lehmer p=
rimality test">Lucas=E2=80=93Lehmer primality test</a> (originated 1856), a=
nd the generalized <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lucas_primality=
_test" title=3D"Lucas primality test">Lucas primality test</a>.<sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-mollin_17-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Prime_number#cite_note-mollin-17"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>17<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Since 1951 all the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Largest_=
known_prime" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Largest known prime">largest kn=
own primes</a> have been found using these tests on <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Computer" title=3D"Computer">computers</a>.<sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-30" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prim=
e_number#cite_note-30"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>a<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The search for ever larger primes has gen=
erated interest outside mathematical circles, through the <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Great_Internet_Mersenne_Prime_Search" title=3D"Grea=
t Internet Mersenne Prime Search">Great Internet Mersenne Prime Search</a> =
and other <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Distributed_computing" t=
itle=3D"Distributed computing">distributed computing</a> projects.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-ziegler_9-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Prime_number#cite_note-ziegler-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-31" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_num=
ber#cite_note-31"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>30<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The idea that prime numbers had few applicati=
ons outside of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pure_mathematics" t=
itle=3D"Pure mathematics">pure mathematics</a><sup id=3D"cite_ref-pure_34-0=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_number=
#cite_note-pure-34"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>b<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup> was shattered in the 1970s when <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Public-key_cryptography" title=3D"Public-key c=
ryptography">public-key cryptography</a> and the <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/RSA_(cryptosystem)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"RSA (cryp=
tosystem)">RSA</a> cryptosystem were invented, using prime numbers as their=
 basis.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-ent-7_35-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_number#cite_note-ent-7-35"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>33<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The increased practical importance of computerized primality testing=
 and factorization led to the development of improved methods capable of ha=
ndling large numbers of unrestricted form.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-pomerance-sci=
am_16-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime=
_number#cite_note-pomerance-sciam-16"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
16<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-36" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_number#cit=
e_note-36"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>34<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-37" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_number#cite_note-37"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>35<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Th=
e mathematical theory of prime numbers also moved forward with the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Green%E2%80%93Tao_theorem" title=3D"Green=
=E2=80=93Tao theorem">Green=E2=80=93Tao theorem</a> (2004) that there are a=
rbitrarily long arithmetic progressions of prime numbers, and <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yitang_Zhang" title=3D"Yitang Zhang">Yitang Zha=
ng</a>'s 2013 proof that there exist infinitely many <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_gap" title=3D"Prime gap">prime gaps</a> of bounded=
 size.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-neale-18-47_38-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_number#cite_note-neale-18-47-38"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>36<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Primality_of_one">Primality=
 of one</h3></div>
<p>Most early Greeks did not even consider 1 to be a number,<sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-crxk-34_39-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Prime_number#cite_note-crxk-34-39"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>37<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-40" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_number#c=
ite_note-40"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>38<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup> so they could not consider its primality. A few sc=
holars in the Greek and later Roman tradition, including <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nicomachus" title=3D"Nicomachus">Nicomachus</a>, <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Iamblichus" title=3D"Iamblichus">Iamb=
lichus</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boethius" title=3D"Boe=
thius">Boethius</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cassiodor=
us" title=3D"Cassiodorus">Cassiodorus</a>, also considered the prime number=
s to be a subdivision of the odd numbers, so they did not consider <span cl=
ass=3D"nowrap">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-in=
line"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"=
display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=
=3D"{\displaystyle 2}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mn>2</mn>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle 2}</annotatio=
n>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/901fc910c19990d0dbaaefe4726ceb1a4e217a0f" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.338ex; width:1.162ex; height:2.176ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle 2}"=
></span>=E2=81=A0</span> to be prime either. However, Euclid and a majority=
 of the other Greek mathematicians considered <span class=3D"nowrap">=E2=81=
=A0<span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"=
mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math=
 xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle 2}"=
>
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mn>2</mn>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle 2}</annotatio=
n>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/901fc910c19990d0dbaaefe4726ceb1a4e217a0f" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.338ex; width:1.162ex; height:2.176ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle 2}"=
></span>=E2=81=A0</span> as prime. The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Mathematics_in_medieval_Islam" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Mathemat=
ics in medieval Islam">medieval Islamic mathematicians</a> largely followed=
 the Greeks in viewing 1 as not being a number.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-crxk-34_=
39-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_nu=
mber#cite_note-crxk-34-39"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>37<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> By the Middle Ages and Renaissance, =
mathematicians began treating 1 as a number, and by the 17th century some o=
f them included it as the first prime number.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-41" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_number#cite_n=
ote-41"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>39<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup> In the mid-18th century, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Christian_Goldbach" title=3D"Christian Goldbach">Christian Goldb=
ach</a> listed 1 as prime in his correspondence with <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Leonhard_Euler" title=3D"Leonhard Euler">Leonhard Euler<=
/a>;<sup id=3D"cite_ref-42" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Prime_number#cite_note-42"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>40<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> however, Euler himself=
 did not consider 1 to be prime.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-43" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_number#cite_note-43"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>41<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup> Many 19th century mathematicians still considered 1 to be prime,<sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-cx_44-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Prime_number#cite_note-cx-44"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>42<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Derrick_Norman_Lehmer" title=3D"Derrick Norman Lehmer=
">Derrick Norman Lehmer</a> included 1 in his <i>list of primes less than t=
en million</i> published in 1914.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConwayGuy19961=
30_45-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime=
_number#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConwayGuy1996130-45"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>43<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Lists of primes =
that included 1 continued to be published as recently <span class=3D"nowrap=
">as 1956.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-46" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_number#cite_note-46"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>44<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-cg-bon-129-130_47-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Prime_number#cite_note-cg-bon-129-130-47"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>45<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></span> Howe=
ver, by the early 20th century mathematicians began to agree that 1 should =
not be listed as prime, but rather in its own special category as a "<a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unit_(ring_theory)" title=3D"Unit (ring =
theory)">unit</a>".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-cx_44-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_number#cite_note-cx-44"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>42<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>If 1 were to be considered a prime, many statements involving primes=
 would need to be awkwardly reworded. For example, the fundamental theorem =
of arithmetic would need to be rephrased in terms of factorizations into pr=
imes greater than 1, because every number would have multiple factorization=
s with any number of copies of&nbsp;1.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-cx_44-2" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_number#cite_note=
-cx-44"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>42<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup> Similarly, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Sieve_of_Eratosthenes" title=3D"Sieve of Eratosthenes">sieve of Eratosthen=
es</a> would not work correctly if it handled 1 as a prime, because it woul=
d eliminate all multiples of 1 (that is, all other numbers) and output only=
 the single number&nbsp;1.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-cg-bon-129-130_47-1" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_number#cite_note=
-cg-bon-129-130-47"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>45<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Some other more technical properties of pri=
me numbers also do not hold for the number 1: for instance, the formulas fo=
r <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euler%27s_totient_function" titl=
e=3D"Euler's totient function">Euler's totient function</a> or for the <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sum-of-divisors_function" class=3D"mw-=
redirect" title=3D"Sum-of-divisors function">sum of divisors function</a> a=
re different for prime numbers than they are for&nbsp;1.<sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-48" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_num=
ber#cite_note-48"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>46<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Elementary_properties">Elem=
entary properties</h2></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Unique_factorization">Uniqu=
e factorization</h3></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
