g/wiki/Prime_number#cite_note-50"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>48<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> This theorem states that ever=
y integer larger than 1 can be written as a product of one or more primes. =
More strongly, this product is unique in the sense that any two prime facto=
rizations of the same number will have the same numbers of copies of the sa=
me primes, although their ordering may differ.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-51" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_number#cite_n=
ote-51"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>49<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup> So, although there are many different ways of finding a=
