<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Formulas_for_primes">Formul=
as for primes</h3></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Formula_for_primes" =
title=3D"Formula for primes">Formula for primes</a></div>
<p>There is no known efficient formula for primes. For example, there is no=
 non-constant <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polynomial" title=3D=
"Polynomial">polynomial</a>, even in several variables, that takes <i>only<=
/i> prime values.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-matiyasevich_60-0" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_number#cite_note-matiyasevi=
ch-60"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>58<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup> However, there are numerous expressions that do encode a=
ll primes, or only primes. One possible formula is based on <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wilson%27s_theorem" title=3D"Wilson's theorem">Wi=
lson's theorem</a> and generates the number 2 many times and all other prim=
es exactly once.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-61" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_number#cite_note-61"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>59<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> There is a=
lso a set of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diophantine_equations=
" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Diophantine equations">Diophantine equatio=
ns</a> in nine variables and one parameter with the following property: the=
 parameter is prime if and only if the resulting system of equations has a =
solution over the natural numbers. This can be used to obtain a single form=
ula with the property that all its <i>positive</i> values are prime.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-matiyasevich_60-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_number#cite_note-matiyasevich-60"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>58<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Other examples of prime-generating formulas come from <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mills%27_theorem" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D=
"Mills' theorem">Mills' theorem</a> and a theorem of <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/E._M._Wright" title=3D"E. M. Wright">Wright</a>. These a=
ssert that there are real constants <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-mat=
h-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11=
y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/Math=
ML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle A&gt;1}">
