</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spectrum_of_a_ring" tit=
le=3D"Spectrum of a ring">spectrum of a ring</a> is a geometric space whose=
 points are the prime ideals of the ring.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-119" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_number#cite_note-=
119"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>117<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic_geome=
try" title=3D"Arithmetic geometry">Arithmetic geometry</a> also benefits fr=
om this notion, and many concepts exist in both geometry and number theory.=
 For example, factorization or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spl=
itting_of_prime_ideals_in_Galois_extensions" title=3D"Splitting of prime id=
eals in Galois extensions">ramification</a> of prime ideals when lifted to =
an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Field_extension" title=3D"Field=
 extension">extension field</a>, a basic problem of algebraic number theory=
, bears some resemblance with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rami=
fied_cover" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Ramified cover">ramification in =
geometry</a>. These concepts can even assist with in number-theoretic quest=
ions solely concerned with integers. For example, prime ideals in the <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ring_of_integers" title=3D"Ring of inte=
gers">ring of integers</a> of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quad=
ratic_number_field" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Quadratic number field">=
quadratic number fields</a> can be used in proving <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Quadratic_reciprocity" title=3D"Quadratic reciprocity">qua=
dratic reciprocity</a>, a statement that concerns the existence of square r=
oots modulo integer prime numbers.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-120" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_number#cite_note-120"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>118<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup> Early attempts to prove <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Fermat%27s_Last_Theorem" title=3D"Fermat's Last Theorem">Fermat's Last The=
orem</a> led to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ernst_Kummer" titl=
e=3D"Ernst Kummer">Kummer</a>'s introduction of <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Regular_prime" title=3D"Regular prime">regular primes</a>, in=
teger prime numbers connected with the failure of unique factorization in t=
he <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cyclotomic_field" title=3D"Cycl=
otomic field">cyclotomic integers</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-121" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_number#cite_note-121=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>119<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup> The question of how many integer prime numbers factor into a=
 product of multiple prime ideals in an algebraic number field is addressed=
 by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chebotarev%27s_density_theorem=
" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Chebotarev's density theorem">Chebotarev's=
 density theorem</a>, which (when applied to the cyclotomic integers) has D=
irichlet's theorem on primes in arithmetic progressions as a special case.<=
sup id=3D"cite_ref-122" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Prime_number#cite_note-122"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
120<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
