<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Computational_methods">Comp=
utational methods</h2></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Gears_large.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-description=
"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/42/Gea=
rs_large.jpg/250px-Gears_large.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=
=3D"340" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"500" data-file-height=
=3D"680"></a><figcaption>The small gear in this piece of farm equipment has=
 13 teeth, a prime number, and the middle gear has 21, relatively prime to =
13.</figcaption></figure>
<p>For a long time, number theory in general, and the study of prime number=
s in particular, was seen as the canonical example of pure mathematics, wit=
h no applications outside of mathematics<sup id=3D"cite_ref-pure_34-1" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_number#cite_=
note-pure-34"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>b<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup> other than the use of prime numbered gear teeth to=
 distribute wear evenly.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-124" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_number#cite_note-124"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>122<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
> In particular, number theorists such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/United_Kingdom" title=3D"United Kingdom">British</a> mathematician =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/G._H._Hardy" title=3D"G. H. Hardy"=
>G. H. Hardy</a> prided themselves on doing work that had absolutely no mil=
itary significance.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-125" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_number#cite_note-125"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>123<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>This vision of the purity of number theory was shattered in the 1970=
s, when it was publicly announced that prime numbers could be used as the b=
asis for the creation of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Public-ke=
y_cryptography" title=3D"Public-key cryptography">public-key cryptography</=
a> algorithms.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-ent-7_35-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_number#cite_note-ent-7-35"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>33<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up>
These applications have led to significant study of <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Algorithm" title=3D"Algorithm">algorithms</a> for computi=
ng with prime numbers, and in particular of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Primality_test" title=3D"Primality test">primality testing</a>, m=
ethods for determining whether a given number is prime. The most basic prim=
ality testing routine, trial division, is too slow to be useful for large n=
umbers. One group of modern primality tests is applicable to arbitrary numb=
ers, while more efficient tests are available for numbers of special types.=
 Most primality tests only tell whether their argument is prime or not. Rou=
tines that also provide a prime factor of composite arguments (or all of it=
s prime factors) are called <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Intege=
r_factorization" title=3D"Integer factorization">factorization</a> algorith=
ms. Prime numbers are also used in computing for <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Checksum" title=3D"Checksum">checksums</a>, <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hash_table" title=3D"Hash table">hash tables</a>, =
and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pseudorandom_number_generator"=
 title=3D"Pseudorandom number generator">pseudorandom number generators</a>=
.
</p>
