table" title=3D"Mathematical table">mathematical tables</a> listing all of =
the primes or prime factorizations up to a given limit were commonly printe=
d.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-129" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Prime_number#cite_note-129"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>127<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The oldest known meth=
od for generating a list of primes is called the sieve of Eratosthenes.<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-130" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Prime_number#cite_note-130"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>128=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The animation shows an opti=
mized variant of this method.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-131" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_number#cite_note-131"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>129<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup> Another more asymptotically efficient sieving method for the same pro=
blem is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sieve_of_Atkin" title=
=3D"Sieve of Atkin">sieve of Atkin</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-132" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_number#cite_note-13=
2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>130<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup> In advanced mathematics, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Sieve_theory" title=3D"Sieve theory">sieve theory</a> applies simila=
r methods to other problems.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-133" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_number#cite_note-133"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>131<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup>
</p>
