</p><p>In contrast, some other algorithms guarantee that their answer will =
always be correct: primes will always be determined to be prime and composi=
tes will always be determined to be composite. For instance, this is true o=
f trial division. The algorithms with guaranteed-correct output include bot=
h <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deterministic_algorithm" title=
=3D"Deterministic algorithm">deterministic</a> (non-random) algorithms, suc=
h as the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/AKS_primality_test" title=
=3D"AKS primality test">AKS primality test</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-tao-aks_=
