<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Special-purpose_algorithms_=
and_the_largest_known_prime">Special-purpose algorithms and the largest kno=
wn prime</h3></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Further information: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_prime=
_numbers" title=3D"List of prime numbers">List of prime numbers</a></div>
<p>In addition to the aforementioned tests that apply to any natural number=
, some numbers of a special form can be tested for primality more quickly. =
For example, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lucas%E2%80%93Leh=
mer_primality_test" title=3D"Lucas=E2=80=93Lehmer primality test">Lucas=E2=
=80=93Lehmer primality test</a> can determine whether a <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mersenne_number" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Merse=
nne number">Mersenne number</a> (one less than a <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Power_of_two" title=3D"Power of two">power of two</a>) is pr=
ime, deterministically, in the same time as a single iteration of the Mille=
r=E2=80=93Rabin test.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-146" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_number#cite_note-146"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>142<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
> This is why since 1992 (as of October&nbsp;2024<sup class=3D"plainlinks n=
oexcerpt noprint asof-tag update" style=3D"display:none;"><a class=3D"exter=
nal text" href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DPrime_number=
&amp;action=3Dedit">[update]</a></sup>) the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Largest_known_prime" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Largest known=
 prime">largest <i>known</i> prime</a> has always been a Mersenne prime.<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-147" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Prime_number#cite_note-147"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14=
3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> It is conjectured that the=
re are infinitely many Mersenne primes.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-148" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_number#cite_note-14=
8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>144<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup>
</p><p>The following table gives the largest known primes of various types.=
 Some of these primes have been found using <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Distributed_computing" title=3D"Distributed computing">distribute=
d computing</a>. In 2009, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grea=
t_Internet_Mersenne_Prime_Search" title=3D"Great Internet Mersenne Prime Se=
arch">Great Internet Mersenne Prime Search</a> project was awarded a US$100=
,000 prize for first discovering a prime with at least 10 million digits.<s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-149" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Prime_number#cite_note-149"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1=
45<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electronic_Frontier_Foundation" title=3D"Electronic Fro=
ntier Foundation">Electronic Frontier Foundation</a> also offers $150,000 a=
nd $250,000 for primes with at least 100 million digits and 1 billion digit=
s, respectively.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-150" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_number#cite_note-150"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>146<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
