<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Other_applications">Other a=
pplications</h2></div>
<p>Prime numbers are of central importance to number theory but also have m=
any applications to other areas within mathematics, including <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abstract_algebra" title=3D"Abstract algebra">ab=
stract algebra</a> and elementary geometry. For example, it is possible to =
place prime numbers of points in a two-dimensional grid so that <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/No-three-in-line_problem" title=3D"No-three-i=
n-line problem">no three are in a line</a>, or so that every triangle forme=
d by three of the points <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heilbronn=
_triangle_problem" title=3D"Heilbronn triangle problem">has large area</a>.=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-172" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Prime_number#cite_note-172"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>167<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Another example is <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eisenstein%27s_criterion" title=3D"Eis=
enstein's criterion">Eisenstein's criterion</a>, a test for whether a <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Irreducible_polynomial" title=3D"Irredu=
cible polynomial">polynomial is irreducible</a> based on divisibility of it=
s coefficients by a prime number and its square.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-173" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_number#cit=
e_note-173"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>168<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Sum_of_knots3.svg" class=3D"mw-file-descripti=
on"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/dc/S=
um_of_knots3.svg/250px-Sum_of_knots3.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"2=
50" height=3D"100" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"300" data-f=
ile-height=3D"120"></a><figcaption>The connected sum of two prime knots</fi=
gcaption></figure>
<p>The concept of a prime number is so important that it has been generaliz=
ed in different ways in various branches of mathematics. Generally, "prime"=
 indicates minimality or indecomposability, in an appropriate sense. For ex=
ample, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_field" class=3D"m=
w-redirect" title=3D"Prime field">prime field</a> of a given field is its s=
mallest subfield that contains both 0 and 1. It is either the field of rati=
onal numbers or a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Finite_field" ti=
tle=3D"Finite field">finite field</a> with a prime number of elements, when=
ce the name.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-174" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_number#cite_note-174"><span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">[</span>169<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Often a sec=
ond, additional meaning is intended by using the word prime, namely that an=
y object can be, essentially uniquely, decomposed into its prime components=
. For example, in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Knot_theory" tit=
le=3D"Knot theory">knot theory</a>, a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Prime_knot" title=3D"Prime knot">prime knot</a> is a <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Knot_(mathematics)" title=3D"Knot (mathematics)">kno=
t</a> that is indecomposable in the sense that it cannot be written as the =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Connected_sum" title=3D"Connected =
sum">connected sum</a> of two nontrivial knots. Any knot can be uniquely ex=
pressed as a connected sum of prime knots.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-175" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_number#cite_note=
-175"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>170<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup> The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_decom=
position_(3-manifold)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Prime decomposition (=
3-manifold)">prime decomposition of 3-manifolds</a> is another example of t=
his type.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-176" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_number#cite_note-176"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>171<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Beyond mathematics and computing, prime numbers have potential conne=
ctions to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quantum_mechanics" title=
=3D"Quantum mechanics">quantum mechanics</a>, and have been used metaphoric=
ally in the arts and literature. They have also been used in <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Evolutionary_biology" title=3D"Evolutionary biol=
ogy">evolutionary biology</a> to explain the life cycles of <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cicada" title=3D"Cicada">cicadas</a>.
</p>
